05443nam a22010455i 9780520932012DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209320127 a10.1525/97805209320122doi  a(DE-B1597)520208  a(OCoLC)1110710889  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS63.2.U5bM37 2005eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a327.56073/09/0452221 aMcAlister, Melani, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEpic Encounters :bCulture, Media, and U.S. Interests in the Middle East since1945 /cMelani McAlister. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (426 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Crossroads ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface To The 2005 Edition -- tPreface To The First Edition -- tIntroduction -- t1. "Benevolent Supremacy" -- t2. The Middle East In African American Cultural Politics, 1955-1972 -- t3. King Tut, Commodity Nationalism, And The Politics Of Oil, 1973-1979 -- t4. The Good Fight -- t5. Iran, Islam, And The Terrorist Threat, 1979-1989 -- t6. Military Multiculturalism In The Gulf War And After, 1990-1999 -- tConclusion<subtitle 9/11 and After: Snapshots on the Road to Empire -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEpic Encounters examines how popular culture has shaped the ways Americans define their "interests" in the Middle East. In this innovative book—now brought up-to-date to include 9/11 and the Iraq war—Melani McAlister argues that U.S. foreign policy, while grounded in material and military realities, is also developed in a cultural context. American understandings of the region are framed by narratives that draw on religious belief, news media accounts, and popular culture. This remarkable and pathbreaking book skillfully weaves lively and accessible readings of film, media, and music with a rigorous analysis of U.S. foreign policy, race politics, and religious history. The new chapter, titled "9/11 and After: Snapshots on the Road to Empire," considers and brilliantly analyzes five images that have become iconic: (1) New York City firemen raising the American flag out of the rubble of the World Trade Center, (2) the televised image of Osama bin-Laden, (3) Afghani women in burqas, (4) the statue of Saddam Hussein being toppled in Baghdad, and (5) the hooded and wired prisoner in Abu Ghraib. McAlister's singular achievement is to illuminate the contexts of these five images both at the time they were taken and as they relate to current events, an accomplishment all the more remarkable since—to paraphrase her new preface—we are today struggling to look backward at something that is still rushing ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMass media and public opinionzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a9/11.  aabu ghraib.  aafghani women.  aafghanistan.  aal qaeda.  acounterterrorism.  acultural studies.  aethnic studies.  afireman.  afirst responders.  aforeign policy.  agovernment policy.  aimperialism.  airaq war.  aisis.  aislam.  amedia.  amiddle east.  amilitary.  anew york.  anonfiction.  aoil.  aorientalism.  aosama bin laden.  apolitics.  apopular culture.  arace.  areligion.  areligious extremism.  areligious fundamentalism.  asaddam hussein.  asocial justice.  asociology.  aterrorism.  aterrorist.  aus foreign relations.  awar on terror.  awar.  aworld history.  aworld trade center.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Califo